Urosternite I with 7+7 macrosetae (
Fig. 17–18
); urosternites II to VII with 5+5 macrosetae; urosternite VIII with 2+2 macrosetae; urosternal macrosetae of medium length or longer, with long barbs. Stylus with a long apical seta with two to three thin barbs and with at least one basal tooth; subapical and ventromedial setae with four to six longer barbs (
Fig. 23
). Cerci almost double the body length, 1.53 and 1.95 times longer than body in the two apparently intact cerci; with six and five primary articles not counting the basal article (
Figs. 19–22
, 
Table 2
). Length of the cerci increasing slightly from the proximal to distal articles; in addition, the number of whorls of macrosetae macroseta number increasing from about six to more than twenty. All primary articles with a distal thin, barbed whorl seta (
Fig. 22
).
